## Research Report: GRDB.swift SchedulingWatchdog Precondition Failure in Async/Swift Concurrency Contexts

### 1. The SchedulingWatchdog Mechanism

Based on the [GRDB source code](https://github.com/groue/GRDB.swift/blob/master/GRDB/Core/SerializedDatabase.swift), here is how GRDB's internal queue safety system works:

**SchedulingWatchdog** is a class that uses GCD queue-specific data (`DispatchQueue.setSpecific` / `DispatchQueue.getSpecific`) to verify that database connections are only used on their designated dispatch queues. The key implementation from the [SchedulingWatchdog source](https://github.com/groue/GRDB.swift):

```swift
final class SchedulingWatchdog: @unchecked Sendable {
    private static let watchDogKey = DispatchSpecificKey<SchedulingWatchdog>()
    private(set) var allowedDatabases: [Database]

    static func allowDatabase(_ database: Database, onQueue queue: DispatchQueue) {
        let watchdog = SchedulingWatchdog(allowedDatabase: database)
        queue.setSpecific(key: watchDogKey, value: watchdog)
    }

    static func preconditionValidQueue(_ db: Database, ...) {
        GRDBPrecondition(allows(db), "Database was not used on the correct thread.", ...)
    }

    static func allows(_ db: Database) -> Bool {
        current?.allows(db) ?? false   // Returns false if current is nil!
    }

    static var current: SchedulingWatchdog? {
        DispatchQueue.getSpecific(key: watchDogKey)   // THE CRITICAL CALL
    }
}
```

When a `SerializedDatabase` is created, GRDB creates a private `DispatchQueue` and attaches a `SchedulingWatchdog` to it via `queue.setSpecific(key:value:)`. Every database operation then checks `SchedulingWatchdog.current` (which calls `DispatchQueue.getSpecific(key:)`) to verify the calling thread belongs to a dispatch queue that has the right watchdog attached.

